50|$|For {{the primary}} market to thrive, {{there must be}} a {{secondary}} market, or aftermarket that provides liquidity for the investment security—where <b>holders</b> <b>of</b> <b>securities</b> can sell them to other investors for cash. Otherwise, few people would purchase primary issues, and, thus, companies and governments would be restricted in raising equity capital (money) for their operations. Organized exchanges constitute the main secondary markets. Many smaller issues and most debt securities trade in the decentralized, dealer-based over-the-counter markets.|$|R
